post_cb({"7979846": {"ParentId": "7979797", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "3", "Body": "<p>From the C++03 standard: \u00a717.4.3.1.2/1</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_7979797_7979846_0\">Certain sets of names and function signatures are always reserved to the implementation:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p id=\"so_7979797_7979846_1\">Each name that contains a double underscore (<code>__</code>) or begins with an underscore followed by an upper-case letter (2.11) is reserved to the implementation for any use.</p></li>\n<li><p id=\"so_7979797_7979846_2\">Each name that begins with an underscore is reserved to the implementation for use as a name in the global namespace.</p></li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The equivalent text is present in C++11 \u00a717.6.4.3.2/1</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "36565", "LastEditorUserId": "36565", "LastEditDate": "2011-11-02T11:53:48.957", "Id": "7979846", "Score": "10", "CreationDate": "2011-11-02T11:51:42.383", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-02T11:53:48.957"}, "7979797": {"CommentCount": "0", "ViewCount": "3245", "PostTypeId": "1", "ClosedDate": "2016-02-27T21:26:25.410", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "CreationDate": "2011-11-02T11:47:39.163", "LastActivityDate": "2012-01-19T09:42:39.233", "Title": "Class members prefixed with underscore (_)", "AcceptedAnswerId": "7979846", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T12:10:41.897", "Id": "7979797", "Score": "5", "Body": "<p>In our projects we decided to prefix member variables and some private/protected methods with underscore (so with \u201c<code>_</code>\u201d).</p>\n<p>During a discussion it was claimed that this is discouraged to do because of some incompatibilities with some compilers/linkers on some platforms. As we want to be a portable as possible I'd like to be sure.</p>\n<p>I also reckon <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5908568/what-is-the-reason-function-names-are-prefixed-with-an-underscore-by-the-compile\">that prefixing globals with underscores in C</a> can be a problem.</p>\n<p>Does the same apply to C++-linkage and if so, in which cases (platforms/compilers/linkers)?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><linker><naming-conventions>", "OwnerUserId": "880584", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "7981284": {"ParentId": "7979797", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "6", "Body": "<p>Personally, I use ''m_name'', with 'm' standing for 'member'.</p>\n<p>By the way, I also use 'p_' for parameters in my functions anf 'g_' for the few unavoidable globals.</p>\n<p>(then I usually get bashed by SO users because it <strong>looks like</strong> hungarian notation ;-) But it is not.)</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "587407", "LastEditorUserId": "587407", "LastEditDate": "2012-01-19T09:42:39.233", "Id": "7981284", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2011-11-02T13:38:06.947", "LastActivityDate": "2012-01-19T09:42:39.233"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_7979797_7979846_0": {"section_id": 6307, "quality": 1.0, "length": 8}, "so_7979797_7979846_1": {"section_id": 6307, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "length": 13}, "so_7979797_7979846_2": {"section_id": 6307, "quality": 1.0, "length": 10}}, "n3337": {"so_7979797_7979846_0": {"section_id": 6064, "quality": 1.0, "length": 8}, "so_7979797_7979846_1": {"section_id": 6064, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "length": 13}, "so_7979797_7979846_2": {"section_id": 6064, "quality": 1.0, "length": 10}}, "n4659": {"so_7979797_7979846_0": {"section_id": 7844, "quality": 0.625, "length": 5}, "so_7979797_7979846_1": {"section_id": 6756, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 12}, "so_7979797_7979846_2": {"section_id": 6756, "quality": 0.9, "length": 9}}}, "7979905": {"ParentId": "7979797", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>Please also look here: <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/228783/what-are-the-rules-about-using-an-underscore-in-a-c-identifier\">What are the rules about using an underscore in a C++ identifier?</a></p>\n<p>I've seen a lot of code using single underscores as a prefix or double underscores in an indentifier and it simply worked. But you never know. The identifiers are reserved and anything may happen, depending on the compiler.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1023911", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T12:02:45.600", "Id": "7979905", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2011-11-02T11:57:00.140", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-02T11:57:00.140"}});